{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16576"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16576"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.04,0.78,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9267"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61385"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"149"},{"type":"tags","id":"1380"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6222"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"7106"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21959"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old female was brought into the Emergency Department as she was noticed by her son to be unsteady on her feet. There was no history of trauma or previous neurological insult.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate combination of clinical features that characterise normal pressure hydrocephalus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ataxia, dysarthria, and nystagmus","Tremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia","Gait disturbance, cognitive impairment, and urinary incontinence","Memory loss, aphasia, and apraxia","Diplopia, dysphagia, and dysarthria"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of normal pressure hydrocephalus (NPH), which is characterised by a classic triad of symptoms -\u003Cstrong\u003E gait disturbance, cognitive impairment, and urinary incontinence\u003C/strong\u003E. The gait disturbance typically presents first and is described as magnetic or apraxic, with short shuffling steps and difficulty initiating movement. The cognitive impairment manifests as subcortical dementia with slowed processing, impaired attention, and executive dysfunction. Urinary symptoms usually begin with urgency and progress to frank incontinence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtaxia, dysarthria, and nystagmus\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of cerebellar disorders such as multiple sclerosis or cerebellar stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETremor, rigidity, and bradykinesia\u003C/strong\u003E are the cardinal features of Parkinson\u0027s disease, which can present similarly but has an asymmetric onset and responds to levodopa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMemory loss, aphasia, and apraxia\u003C/strong\u003E are more typical of Alzheimer\u0027s disease, which presents primarily with cognitive symptoms rather than the gait and urinary features seen in NPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiplopia, dysphagia, and dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E are features of brainstem dysfunction or conditions affecting cranial nerves, such as myasthenia gravis or progressive bulbar palsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENPH is important to recognise as it is one of the few potentially reversible causes of dementia. Diagnosis is supported by neuroimaging showing ventriculomegaly out of proportion to cortical atrophy. A positive response to large-volume CSF removal (tap test) can help predict which patients will benefit from ventriculoperitoneal shunting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal pressure hydrocephalus is characterised by the clinical triad of gait disturbance, cognitive impairment, and urinary incontinence.","Early recognition of normal pressure hydrocephalus is important as symptoms may be reversible with CSF shunting.","Gait disturbance typically precedes cognitive and urinary symptoms in normal pressure hydrocephalus."],"references":["Shprecher D, Schwalb J, Kurlan R. Normal pressure hydrocephalus: diagnosis and treatment. Curr Neurol Neurosci Rep. 2008 Sep;8(5):371-6. doi: 10.1007/s11910-008-0058-2. PMID: 18713572; PMCID: PMC2674287.","Patel S, Ditamo M, Mangal R, Gould M, Ganti L. Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus. Cureus. 2023 Feb 18;15(2):e35131. doi: 10.7759/cureus.35131. PMID: 36949988; PMCID: PMC10026533.","Oliveira LM, Nitrini R, Rom\u00e1n GC. Normal-pressure hydrocephalus: A critical review. Dement Neuropsychol. 2019 Apr-Jun;13(2):133-143. doi: 10.1590/1980-57642018dn13-020001. Erratum in: Dement Neuropsychol. 2019 Jul-Sep;13(3):361. doi: 10.1590/1980-57642018dn13-030016. PMID: 31285787; PMCID: PMC6601311."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61385"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16576"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61385"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T05:46:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T05:46:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9267"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75872"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tag